The two Poland
The European Parliament recently condemned the attempt by the Polish government to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former foreign minister - who led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign yet another declaration stating that he was not an agent of the secret police during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the behavior of the Polish government and Geremek stated that the law on lustration [decommunization] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A May 11 decision by the constitutional court largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to keep his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government whose only aim is to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best in him, while the second unleashes the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reemerge into the open in 1989, in the wake of the "perestroika" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes of government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revisionists, post-communist provincial agitators, xenophobic and antisemitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the mouthpiece of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
One sees worrying signs everywhere: the authority of Justice is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is questioned, officials are bought, and the role of the prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more delinquency, the market economy but also the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a widening income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also caused fear of the foreign and fear of an invasion by Western mass culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the State, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the ruling coalition governs, combining the conservative potion of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the firmament.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous activists of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Thus, the sense of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and vengeful energy directed both against the former enemies and the old friends who seemed to be coming out unscathed.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest achievement of Poland in 300 years.
To them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be righted.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a large purge.
According to initial estimates, the lustration should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people targeted for lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and prohibited from practicing their profession for ten years.

Cardinal Dziwisz of Cracovie reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity and baseless accusations".
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The aim of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, and not a hunt for suspects, proven or not, of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither the economic reforms of Leszek Balcerowicz, nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO, nor of the European Union.
Today, two Poles are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear and revenge is fighting the Poland of hope, courage and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends from the underground and from prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional court leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the will for freedom, or what it has produced, a democratic state.
